---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Manifesto — Syncopate" description="Why we built Syncopate: smart, programmable Spaces where conversations do the work.">
  <section class="section manifesto-hero">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="manifesto-header">
        <span class="section-label">Our Manifesto</span>
        <h1>"Power to<br />the users."</h1>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section manifesto-content">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="prose">
        <h2>The Problem</h2>
        <p>
          Every business runs on conversations — questions, confirmations, updates, negotiations.
          But the tools that track those conversations live somewhere else entirely.
        </p>
        <p>The result is a loop everyone recognises:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Talk to your client</strong> — over WhatsApp, email, wherever</li>
          <li><strong>Open the dashboard</strong> — which knows nothing about what you just discussed</li>
          <li><strong>Re-type everything</strong> — into forms that nobody enjoys filling out</li>
          <li><strong>Switch back to chat</strong> — to relay the update and get confirmation</li>
          <li><strong>Hope nothing was lost</strong> — because the conversation and the record live in two different places</li>
          <li><strong>Repeat forever</strong></li>
        </ol>
        <p>
          The conversation already contains everything.
          <strong>Why are we still copying it into dashboards?</strong>
        </p>

        <hr />

        <h2>Our Bet</h2>
        <p>
          The next wave of business tools doesn't ask you to switch between chat and dashboards.
          It makes <strong>the conversation itself smart enough to do the work</strong>.
        </p>
        <p>
          AI has made natural language a reliable interface for structured operations. People can
          talk to bots, run commands, and get things done — all inside a conversation. The dashboard
          becomes the fallback for big-picture views, not the thing you live in all day.
        </p>

        <hr />

        <h2>Principles</h2>

        <h3>1. Conversations Are the Interface</h3>
        <p>
          The primary way people interact with Syncopate is by talking — to bots, to your team,
          through slash commands. Every action inside a Space is automatically recorded. The conversation
          <em>is</em> the audit trail.
        </p>

        <h3>2. Spaces Are Smart and Programmable</h3>
        <p>
          Every Space is backed by bots that understand your business context. They answer questions,
          look things up, and execute tasks. Slash commands let anyone — staff or client — get things
          done without ever touching a form.
        </p>

        <h3>3. Trust Is Granular, Not Binary</h3>
        <p>
          Real business isn't "inside or outside." Staff, clients, and service providers coexist in
          the same Space with scoped visibility. Everyone sees only what they should.
        </p>

        <h3>4. Bots Are Participants, Not Features</h3>
        <p>
          The bot is a participant in the conversation — it has full context of the Space, can
          answer questions, draft responses, and execute actions after human confirmation. This
          is <strong>human-in-the-loop</strong> by design.
        </p>

        <h3>5. Hubs Are Market-Agnostic</h3>
        <p>
          Syncopate doesn't prescribe what your business looks like. The platform provides Spaces,
          messaging, permissions, and AI. Your <strong>Hub</strong> configures it for your domain —
          with bots, commands, and workflows tailored to how you actually work.
        </p>

        <h3>6. Your Users Are Yours</h3>
        <p>
          On other platforms, the people you invite belong to that platform — anyone can message them,
          scammers can target them. On Syncopate, users only hear from Hubs they've joined.
          You control the entire communication boundary.
        </p>

        <hr />

        <h2>What We're NOT Building</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Another Slack or Discord</strong> — We're not building internal team chat</li>
          <li><strong>Another dashboard</strong> — We're replacing dashboards as the primary interface</li>
          <li><strong>A platform that owns your users</strong> — Your clients belong to your Hub, not us</li>
          <li><strong>A walled garden</strong> — Your data is exportable, always</li>
          <li><strong>A chatbot that sounds smart but does nothing</strong> — Real bots that do real work</li>
        </ul>

        <hr />

        <h2>Our Commitments</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Conversation-first, dashboard-fallback</strong> — The Space is always the primary interface</li>
          <li><strong>Smart by default</strong> — Every Space comes with bots that understand context</li>
          <li><strong>Programmable</strong> — Slash commands and the Bot SDK let you customise everything</li>
          <li><strong>Granular trust</strong> — Mixed-trust environments are the default</li>
          <li><strong>Your data, exportable</strong> — Full export anytime, standard formats</li>
          <li><strong>Your users, your rules</strong> — No spam, no platform-level contact</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="manifesto-cta">
          <p><em>Syncopate: Give your clients a conversation worth coming back to.</em></p>
          <a href="/#waitlist" class="btn btn-primary" style="margin-top: 1rem;">Join the Waitlist</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .manifesto-hero {
    padding-top: 160px;
    padding-bottom: 60px;
    background: var(--gradient-glow);
  }

  .manifesto-header {
    text-align: center;
    max-width: 650px;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }

  .manifesto-content {
    padding-top: 40px;
  }

  .manifesto-cta {
    text-align: center;
    margin-top: 3rem;
    padding-top: 2rem;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--border-subtle);
  }

  .manifesto-cta p {
    font-size: 1.15rem;
    color: var(--text-primary);
  }
</style>
